@startuml k8s Storage PV PVC NFS
!theme plain
title Kubernetes Storage: PV, PVC, StorageClass, and NFS (on k3s)

skinparam componentStyle rectangle
skinparam backgroundColor #FAFAFA

actor "Me\n(Developer)" as me

' ==========================================================
' NFS SERVER -- external storage provider
' ==========================================================
node "NFS Server\n(another machine or VM)\nIP: 192.168.1.50" as nfs_host #Wheat {
  database "Exported directory\n/srv/nfs/k8s\n(shared filesystem)" as nfs_export
  component "nfsd\n(NFS daemon)" as nfsd
}

' ==========================================================
' MY COMPUTER -- the k3s cluster
' ==========================================================
node "My Computer\n(k3s cluster, 1 node)" as host #LightCyan {

  package "k3s CLUSTER" as cluster #LightBlue {

    ' ------- Cluster-scope (no namespace) -------
    package "Cluster-scope resources\n(no namespace)" as cluster_scope #Lavender {

      component "StorageClass:\nnfs-client\n(provisioner:\nnfs-subdir-\nexternal-provisioner)" as sc

      storage "PV-static\ncapacity: 5Gi\naccessMode: RWX\nnfs:\n  server: 192.168.1.50\n  path: /srv/nfs/k8s/static" as pv_static
      storage "PV-dynamic-001\n(auto-created by\nprovisioner)\ncapacity: 2Gi\naccessMode: RWX" as pv_dyn

      component "nfs-subdir-\nexternal-provisioner\n(pod, watches PVCs)" as provisioner
    }

    ' ------- Namespace: my-app -------
    package "Namespace: my-app" as ns #White {

      component "PVC-A (static)\nrequests: 5Gi\naccessMode: RWX\nvolumeName: PV-static" as pvc_a
      component "PVC-B (dynamic)\nrequests: 2Gi\naccessMode: RWX\nstorageClassName: nfs-client" as pvc_b

      component "Deployment:\nmy-service" as deploy

      package "Pod replica 1" as pod1 #LightGreen {
        component "container\nmount: /data" as c1
        component "Volume\n(PVC-B)" as v1
      }

      package "Pod replica 2" as pod2 #LightGreen {
        component "container\nmount: /data" as c2
        component "Volume\n(PVC-B)" as v2
      }

      package "Pod (legacy)" as pod3 #LightYellow {
        component "container\nmount: /shared" as c3
        component "Volume\n(PVC-A)" as v3
      }
    }
  }
}

' ==========================================================
' RELATIONSHIPS
' ==========================================================

' --- Static provisioning flow ---
me -[#blue]-> pv_static    : 1a. admin creates PV\n(static, points to NFS path)
me -[#blue]-> pvc_a        : 2a. user creates PVC\n(binds to PV-static)
pvc_a -[#blue,dashed]-> pv_static : bound (1:1)

' --- Dynamic provisioning flow ---
me -[#orange]-> pvc_b      : 1b. user creates PVC\nreferencing StorageClass
pvc_b ..> sc               : asks StorageClass\nto provision
sc -[#orange]-> provisioner: triggers
provisioner -[#orange]-> nfsd : mkdir new subfolder on NFS
provisioner -[#orange]-> pv_dyn : creates PV dynamically
pvc_b -[#orange,dashed]-> pv_dyn : bound (auto)

' --- PV -> NFS link ---
pv_static -[#red]-> nfs_export : nfs mount path:\n/srv/nfs/k8s/static
pv_dyn    -[#red]-> nfs_export : nfs mount path:\n/srv/nfs/k8s/dyn-001

' --- Pod uses PVC ---
deploy ..> pod1 : manages
deploy ..> pod2 : manages
pod1 --> v1 : volumes:\n - name: data\n   pvc: PVC-B
pod2 --> v2 : volumes:\n - name: data\n   pvc: PVC-B
pod3 --> v3 : volumes:\n - name: shared\n   pvc: PVC-A

v1 ..> pvc_b : reference
v2 ..> pvc_b : reference
v3 ..> pvc_a : reference

c1 -[#green]-> v1 : mounts at /data
c2 -[#green]-> v2 : mounts at /data
c3 -[#green]-> v3 : mounts at /shared

' --- Actual file access at runtime ---
v1 -[#purple,dashed]-> nfs_export : NFS mount (kernel)
v2 -[#purple,dashed]-> nfs_export : NFS mount (kernel)
v3 -[#purple,dashed]-> nfs_export : NFS mount (kernel)

' ==========================================================
' NOTES
' ==========================================================

note right of nfs_host
  NFS is just a file server.
  It exposes a directory over
  the network using the NFS
  protocol. Any client (Linux,
  K8s pod, etc.) can mount it
  like a local folder.
end note

note bottom of sc
  StorageClass defines:
  * which provisioner to use
  * what parameters to pass
  * default reclaim policy

  In k3s, the default is
  "local-path" (writes to
  local disk). Add "nfs-client"
  via Helm for NFS support:
  helm install nfs-provisioner \\
    nfs-subdir-external-provisioner \\
    --set nfs.server=192.168.1.50 \\
    --set nfs.path=/srv/nfs/k8s
end note

note left of provisioner
  This is a regular pod that
  watches for PVCs with
  storageClassName: nfs-client.
  When it sees one, it creates
  a subfolder on the NFS share
  and a matching PV object.
end note

note bottom of pvc_a
  STATIC provisioning:
  Admin pre-creates PV first.
  PVC then "claims" it by
  matching size + access mode
  (or explicit volumeName).

  Use when: NFS share already
  exists with specific data
  that pods need to consume.
end note

note bottom of pvc_b
  DYNAMIC provisioning:
  User just creates a PVC
  referencing a StorageClass.
  PV is created automatically.

  Use when: pods need their
  own private storage, no
  pre-existing data needed.
end note

note top of ns
  PVC lives in a NAMESPACE.
  PV lives at CLUSTER scope.
  A PVC in namespace "my-app"
  CANNOT see PVCs in other
  namespaces, but they all
  share the PV pool.
end note

note right of pod1
  Both pod 1 and pod 2 mount
  the SAME PVC (PVC-B). They
  share the same NFS folder.

  This is possible because
  NFS supports RWX (Read-
  Write-Many). Block-storage
  PVs (EBS, local-path) only
  support RWO -- one pod at
  a time.
end note

note bottom of cluster
  Pod-to-Storage lifecycle:

  1. User writes PVC YAML
  2. K8s binds PVC -> PV
     (static or dynamic)
  3. Pod's volumes[] references
     PVC by name
  4. kubelet on the node mounts
     the PV's backing storage
     (NFS in this case)
  5. Container sees it as a
     regular directory at
     mountPath (e.g. /data)
  6. App reads/writes files
     normally -- they end up
     on the NFS server.
end note

@enduml
